  "prompt": "Why do IIT's and NIT's in India get so much domestic admiration when most of them do not feature anywhere in top 100 globally?",
  "response": "The admiration for Indian Institutes of Technology (IITs) and National Institutes of Technology (NITs) within India can be attributed to several factors, despite their rankings not always being in the top 100 globally:\n\n1. **Historical Prestige and Reputation**: IITs were established with the aim of fostering technological and scientific education in post-independence India. The first IIT was set up in 1951, and over the decades, these institutes have built a strong reputation for producing high-quality engineers and technocrats. The rigorous entrance examination process, known as the Joint Entrance Examination (JEE), further adds to their prestige.\n\n2. **Alumni Success**: Many IIT and NIT alumni have gone on to achieve significant success globally, both in academia and industry. Notable alumni include CEOs of multinational corporations, successful entrepreneurs, and prominent academics. This success story contributes to the institutes' esteemed status.\n\n3. **Domestic Impact**: Within India, IITs and NITs have played a crucial role in the country's technological advancement and economic growth. They are often seen as the backbone of India's engineering and technological sectors, and their contributions are highly valued domestically.\n\n4. **Selective Admission Process**: The extremely competitive nature of the entrance exams (JEE for IITs and JEE Main for NITs) means that only a small percentage of applicants are admitted. This selectivity enhances the perceived value and prestige of these institutions.\n\n5. **Government Support and Funding**: As premier institutes, IITs and NITs receive significant government funding and support, which helps them maintain high standards of education and research facilities. This support further solidifies their standing within the country.\n\n6. **Cultural Significance**: In Indian society, getting into an IIT or NIT is often seen as a mark of exceptional academic achievement. The rigorous preparation for the entrance exams and the subsequent admission into these institutes are viewed as significant accomplishments.\n\n7. **Global Rankings Limitations**: Global university rankings often have criteria that may not fully reflect the strengths and contributions of IITs and NITs. Factors such as research output, internationalization, and industry income can be weighted differently, and some of these metrics may not align with the primary objectives and achievements of these institutes within India.\n\n8. **Economic Value**: Graduates from IITs and NITs are highly sought after by employers, both in India and internationally, often commanding high salaries and excellent job prospects. This economic value adds to their allure and prestige.\n\nWhile IITs and NITs may not always rank in the top 100 globally, their impact and reputation within India are substantial, driven by a combination of historical prestige, alumni success, domestic contributions, and the high level of competition for admission.",
